he subjects were given the Peabody Picture Vocabulary Test (Dunn, 1965), a wide ly used verbal intelligence test. The subjects' mental age scores were used as the unit of analysis. Form A was used on the pretest, Form B on the immediate posttest, and Form A on the delayed posttest. An alternate form reliability coefficient of .84 was reported in the PPVT manual.

out_desc_tool: All three mathematical tasks were z-standardised and their average then used as comprehensive math score. The reliability of this score was acceptable to good (Cronbach’s αt1/t2 = .81/.77). All subtests had been used in previous research (see, for example, Niklas, Cohrssen, and Tayler 2016  Niklas and Schneider 2014) and are good predictors of children later mathematical abilities in school.

out_desc_tool: The dependent measure of interest in the pre- and post-test was whether children performed informative and meaningful experiments or actions. An experiment was meaningful when the child tested one variable at a time. For instance, the child varied block orientation while keeping block position constant or otherwise, it was counted each time the child did this. We also observed whether the child performed other informative actions. For instance, the child moved the box, while keeping other variables constant, or the child hit on the top of the box while keeping other variables constant.
Children’s receptive knowledge of taught and control words was tested with a picture vocabulary test similar to the PPVT (Dunn & Dunn, 2007).

out_desc_tool: For this test, an examiner presents a series of individual cards containing one colored picture (photograph or illustration), one at a time, to a child. The pictures on the cards consist of objects found in the natural environment such as in the community, at home, or in school. The order of the cards is completely random and different for each child. The child must name as many pictures as he or she can in one minute  the child’s score is the total number of pictures named correctly.

The Visual Perception Aspects Test, developed by Sylvia Clutten in South Africa in 2009, was used to measure visuospatial skills in this study. nine visual perceptual aspects are as follows  VD, visual form constancy, VM, VSM, visual– spatial relationships, position-in-space, visual closure, visual figure-ground, and visual analysis and synthesis. Only three of these visuospatial perception aspects were considered in this study
